</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="names">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">kywe-thwe</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">taung-tangyi</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Himalaya (Nepal to Bhutan), India. In Myanmar, found in Mandalay, Rakhine, Taninthayi.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="uses">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Whole Plant</emphasis>
: Decoction used to treat fever, neuralgia, and rheumatism. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Root</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Stem Bark</emphasis>
: Used as laxative, carminative, stomachic. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Root</emphasis>
: Used to treat diabetes and liver complaints.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="99" pageNumber="100" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="99" pageNumber="100">
In India the leaf is used as a carminative, galactagogue, and in a decoction for flatulence and colic; the root is used as a laxative, stomachic, tonic, and is a component of the Ayurvedic drug dasmula used for fever (
<bibRefCitation author="Jain, SK" journalOrPublisher="Phytotherapy Research" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B50" refString="Jain, SK, DeFilipps, RA, 1991. Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." year="1991">Jain and DeFilipps 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
